{{About|the painting Au Lapin Agile by [[Pablo Picasso]]|the cabaret club in [[Montmartre]], [[Paris]]|Lapin Agile}} {{Infobox artwork/wikidata|image=Pablo Picasso, 1905, Au Lapin Agile (At the Lapin Agile), oil on canvas, 99.1 x 100.3 cm, Metropolitan Museum of Art.jpg}} '''''Au Lapin Agile''''' is a 1905 painting by [[Pablo Picasso]]. The harlequin is a self-portrait of the artist. The woman represents his lover Germaine Pichot, formerly the obsession of [[Carlos Casagemas]], a friend of Picasso who committed suicide in 1901 because of an unreturned love for Pichot.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2001/jul/07/art The Guardian, Jonathan Jones, ''The Three Dancers, Pablo Picasso (1925)'']</ref> In 1907 Pichot appeared as one of the models in Picasso's ''[[Les Demoiselles d'Avignon]]''.<ref name="Washington Post - 18Mar2007 - $40.7 Million For Picasso Work, $269 Million Sale at Sotheby's">{{cite news|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-1223345.html|title=$40.7 Million For Picasso Work; $269 Million Sale at Sotheby's|last=Tully|first=Judd|date=November 16, 1989|work=[[The Washington Post]]|publisher=via [[HighBeam Research]]|accessdate=9 May 2012}} {{subscription required}}</ref>
==Ownership history== Frédéric Gérard (depicted in the painting playing the guitar) commissioned the painting and exhibited it at its namesake Montmartre cabaret, the [[Lapin Agile|Au Lapin Agile]], from 1905 to 1912.<ref name="met48162">{{cite web|url=http://www.metmuseum.org/collection/the-collection-online/search/486162|title=At the Lapin Agile|publisher= The Metropolitan Museum of Art}}</ref>
On November 27, 1989, [[Walter H. Annenberg]] bought the painting at auction from the [[Joan Whitney Payson]] family for $40.7 million. He gave the painting to the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]].<ref name="met48162" /><ref name="Washington Post - 18Mar2007 - $40.7 Million For Picasso Work, $269 Million Sale at Sotheby's" />
